Now I have the complete picture. Let me provide the finding:

**VERDICT: confirmed** — `subsystem/src/main/java/org/wildfly/subsystem/service/capability/CapabilityServiceInstaller.java` has a **default mode regression** and the new `BlockingBuilder` interface **lacks a `blocking()` method**.

**Finding 1 - Default mode mismatch (line ~267 in the new DefaultBlockingBuilder constructor):**

The old `DefaultBuilder` inherited from `AbstractUnaryBuilder` → `AbstractBuilder`, which in the base code initializes `mode = ServiceController.Mode.ON_DEMAND` (line 299 of `service/src/main/java/org/wildfly/service/Installer.java`).

The new `DefaultBlockingBuilder`'s main constructor does NOT call `withDefaultMode()`:
```java
DefaultBlockingBuilder(RuntimeCapability<Void> capability, Supplier<T> provider, Function<? super T, ? extends V> mapper) {
    super(provider, mapper);
    this.capability = capability;
    // No withDefaultMode call here!
}
```

It inherits from `AbstractBlockingValueBuilder` → `AbstractValueBuilder` → new `AbstractBuilder`, whose default is `ServiceController.Mode.PASSIVE`. Only the copy constructor (used by `map()`) calls `this.withDefaultMode(ServiceController.Mode.ON_DEMAND)`. So `BlockingBuilder.of(capability, supplier).build()` gets `PASSIVE` instead of `ON_DEMAND` — a behavioral change.

**Finding 2 - Missing `blocking()` method on new `BlockingBuilder` (line ~44-77 in new interface):**

The old `Builder<T,V>` interface extended `BlockingBuilder<Builder<T,V>>` which declared `blocking()`. The new `BlockingBuilder<T,V>` interface extends `Installer.BlockingValueBuilder` which does NOT have a `blocking()` method. The deprecated legacy `Builder<T,V>` interface (line ~170) still extends `Installer.BlockingBuilder<Builder<T,V>>` and retains the `blocking()` method for backward compatibility, but callers using the new `BlockingBuilder.of()` API have no way to enable blocking instrumentation.
